%T A394227 32633262623232,232233233262336,23333333233223232,32323366336223232,
%U A394227 62233233232223232,636222622662623232,22262623323232223232,23222222323326222336,32622363633222623232,366222623632326623232,3262226222332222263263232
%N A394227 Positive integers whose decimal digits are 2, 3, or 6, and that are divisible by the product of their digits.
%C A394227 Such numbers may be called "10-spacious", where b-spacious integers are those with b-ary (b >= 7) expansion containing only digits 2, 3, 6, that are divisible by the product of these digits.
%C A394227 Conjecture: The sequence is infinite. Idea: If one assumes the heuristic that a "decimal with digits 2, 3, 6 is divisible by P, the product of its digits, with probability 1/P", then the expected number of terms with M digits is exactly 1 using 1/2 + 1/3 + 1/6 = 1 and the trinomial expansion formula (see Alkauskas link).
%C A394227 For n>3, a(n) must contain at least 2 different digits. - _Chai Wah Wu_, Mar 19 2026
%H A394227 Giedrius Alkauskas, <a href="https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/5128260/integers-n-with-decimal-digits-in-the-set-2-3-6-which-are-divisible-by-t">Integers N with decimal digits in the set {2,3,6} which are divisible by their digit product</a>, Mathematics Stack Exchange, 2026.
%e A394227 2232 is a term since it is divisible by 2*2*3*2 = 24.
%e A394227 32633262623232 is a term since 32633262623232 = 2^9 * 3^10 * 31 * 34819 is divisible by the product of its digits, 2^6 * 3^5 * 6^3.
%o A394227 (Python)
%o A394227 from itertools import count, product
%o A394227 def a(): # generator of terms
%o A394227     for M in count(1):
%o A394227         for t in product((2,3,6), repeat=M):
%o A394227             n, p = 0, 1
%o A394227             for d in t:
%o A394227                 n = 10 * n + d
%o A394227                 p *= d
%o A394227             if n % p == 0:
%o A394227                 yield n
%o A394227 for k in a(): print(k, end=", ")
%Y A394227 Subsequence of A007602.
